Toronto stocks end weaker with bonds ahead of data . Toronto stocks finished weaker on Thursday , depressed by sagging bonds as nervous investors awaited Friday ' s Canadian and U . S . inflation data . The TSE 300 Composite Index dropped 27 . 52 points to close at 5136 . 25 in heavy volume of 89 . 2 million shares valued at C $ 1 . 25 billion . Declining stocks easily outpaced advances 531 to 347 with 281 issues ending flat . " The market is very sensitive to economic data , particularly numbers that could affect interest rates , " said Ira Katzin , an investment advisor with Richardson Greenshields of Canada Ltd . The U . S . non - farm payrolls report for August is considered a key measure of U . S . economic growth . Katzin said some investors were worried that a strong number could result in higher interest rates . Canada ' s August labor force survey is also due on Friday . All but one of Toronto ' s 14 sub - groups ended the day on the weak side . Gold , financial services , conglomerates and transportation posted the heaviest losses . The only bright spot was consumer products , which gained 44 points . - - - HOT STOCKS - - - * Seagram Co Ltd pushed the consumer product group higher , finishing up 0 . 80 at 46 . The entertaining and beverage giant reported improved second - quarter results earlier today . * Forestry products giant Domtar Inc topped active stocks , rising 0 . 10 to 11 . 30 on 4 . 3 million shares . Traders said the heavy action was linked to the redemption of the company ' s convertible debentures , but takeover rumors were also swirling around the Quebec - based pulp and paper firm . * Among weak stocks , Potash Corp of Saskatchewan Inc lost 2 . 70 to 98 . 50 . A U . S . brokerage earlier today downgraded Potash Corp ' s merger target Arcadian Corp . - - Reuters Toronto Bureau ( 416 ) 941 - 8100 
